elDate = April 10, 2019<ref name=\"jp-novel-6\">{{cite web|url=https://dengekibunko.jp/product/86/321811001103.html|title=\uff18\uff16\u2015\u30a8\u30a4\u30c6\u30a3\u30b7\u30c3\u30af\u30b9\u2015Ep.6 \u2015\u660e\u3051\u306d\u3070\u3053\u305d\u591c\u306f\u6c38\u304f\u2015|language=Japanese|publisher=[[ASCII Media Works]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| OriginalISBN    = 9784049124613\n| LicensedRelDate = \u2014\n| LicensedISBN    = \n| ChapterList     =\n| LicensedTitle   = The Rising Sun Does Not Rise for the Eternal Night\n| OriginalTitle   = \u660e\u3051\u306d\u3070\u3053\u305d\u591c\u306f\u6c38\u304f\n| TranslitTitle   = Akeneba Koso Yoru wa Nagaku\n| Summary         = \n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n| VolumeNumber    = 7\n| OriginalRelDate = September 10, 2019<ref name=\"jp-novel-7\">{{cite web|url=https://dengekibunko.jp/product/86/321906000033.html|title=\uff18\uff16\u2015\u30a8\u30a4\u30c6\u30a3\u30b7\u30c3\u30af\u30b9\u2015Ep.7 \u2015\u30df\u30b9\u30c8\u2015|language=Japanese|publisher=[[ASCII Media Works]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| OriginalISBN    = 9784049127980\n| LicensedRelDate = \u2014\n| LicensedISBN    = \n| ChapterList     =\n| LicensedTitle   = Mist\n| OriginalTitle   = \u30df\u30b9\u30c8\n| TranslitTitle   = Misuto\n| Summary         = \n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n| VolumeNumber    = 8\n| OriginalRelDate = May 9, 2020<ref name=\"jp-novel-8\">{{cite web|url=https://dengekibunko.jp/product/86/322002000076.html|title=\uff18\uff16\u2015\u30a8\u30a4\u30c6\u30a3\u30b7\u30c3\u30af\u30b9\u2015Ep.8 \u2015\u30ac\u30f3\u30b9\u30e2\u30fc\u30af\u30fb\u30aa\u30f3\u30fb\u30b6\u30fb\u30a6\u30a9\u30fc\u30bf\u30fc\u2015|language=Japanese|publisher=[[ASCII Media Works]]|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n| OriginalISBN    = 9784049131857\n| LicensedRelDate = \u2014\n| LicensedISBN    = \n| ChapterList     =\n| LicensedTitle   = Gun Smoke On the Water\n| OriginalTitle   = \u30ac\u30f3\u30b9\u30e2\u30fc\u30af\u30fb\u30aa\u30f3\u30fb\u30b6\u30fb\u30a6\u30a9\u30fc\u30bf\u30fc\n| TranslitTitle   = Gan\tSumoku On Za Uota\t\n| Summary         = \n}}\n{{Graphic novel list/footer}}\n\n===Manga===\nA [[manga]] adaptation by Motoki Yoshihara has been serialized in [[Square Enix]]'s [[seinen manga|''seinen'' manga]] magazine ''[[Young Gangan]]'' since 2018. It has been collected in two ''[[tank\u014dbon]]'' volumes. A second manga adaptation titled ''Gakuen 86'' by Suzume Somemiya has been announced. It will be serialized in [[Media Factory]]'s ''seinen'' manga magazine ''[[Monthly Comic Alive]]''.<ref name=\"ANN1\"/>\n\n{{Graphic novel list/header\n| Language     = Japanese\n| OneLanguage  = yes\n| Width        = 75%\n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n| VolumeNumber = 1\n| RelDate      = October 10, 2018<ref name=\"jp-manga-1\">{{cite web|url=https://magazine.jp.square-enix.com/top/comics/detail/9784757558700/|title=86\u30fc\u30a8\u30a4\u30c6\u30a3\u30b7\u30c3\u30af\u30b9\u30fc 1|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Young Gangan]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| ISBN         = 9784757558700\n| ChapterList  =\n| Summary      = \n}}\n{{Graphic novel list\n| VolumeNumber = 2\n| RelDate      = September 10, 2019<ref name=\"jp-manga-2\">{{cite web|url=https://magazine.jp.square-enix.com/top/comics/detail/9784757562783/|title=86\u30fc\u30a8\u30a4\u30c6\u30a3\u30b7\u30c3\u30af\u30b9\u30fc 2|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Young Gangan]]|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| ISBN         = 9784757562783\n| ChapterList  =\n| Summary      = \n}}\n{{Graphic novel list/footer}}\n\n===Anime===\nAn [[anime]] television series adaptation was announced in a livestream commemorating the first anniversary of [[Kadokawa Corporation|Kadokawa]]'s \"Kimirano\" light novel website on March 15, 2020.<ref name=\"ANN1\"/> It is produced by [[A-1 Pictures]] and directed by Toshimasa Ishii, with Toshiya Ono writing the scripts, and Tetsuya Kawakami designing the characters. The series is scheduled to air in 2020.<ref name=\"ANN2\">{{cite web|first=Crystalyn|last=Hodgkins|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-03-22/86-sci-fi-battle-anime-reveals-cast-staff-2020-premiere/.157809|title='86' Sci-Fi Battle Anime Reveals Cast, Staff, 2020 Premiere|work=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 22, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe light novel won the Grand Prize at the 24th [[Dengeki Novel Prize]] award in 2016.<ref name=\"ANN2\"/> The light novel also ranked second in 2018 in [[Takarajimasha]]'s annual light novel guide book ''[[Kono Light Novel ga Sugoi!]]'', in the ''[[bunkobon]]'' category.<ref>{{cite web|first=Rafael Antonio|last=Pineda|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-11-24/kono-light-novel-ga-sugoi-reveals-2018-series-ranking/.124444|title=Kono Light Novel ga Sugoi! Reveals 2018 Series Ranking|work=[[Anime News Network]]|date=November 24, 2017|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> It ranked fifth in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|first=Rafael Antonio|last=Pineda|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-11-23/kono-light-novel-ga-sugoi-reveals-2019-series-ranking/.139859|title=Kono Light Novel ga Sugoi! Reveals 2019 Series Ranking|work=[[Anime News Network]]|date=November 23, 2018|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://dengekibunko.jp/product/86/|Official light novel website}} {{in lang|ja}}\n*{{Official website|https://magazine.jp.square-enix.com/yg/introduction/86/|Official manga website}} {{in lang|ja}}\n*{{Official website|https://anime-86.com/|Official anime website}} {{in lang|ja}}\n*{{ann|light novel|21185}}\n*{{ann|anime|23089}}\n\n{{Gangan Comics manga franchises}}\n{{A-1 Pictures}}\n\n[[Category:2017 Japanese novels]]\n[[Category:A-1 Pictures]]\n[[Category:Anime and manga based on light novels]]\n[[Category:Dengeki Bunko]]\n[[Category:Gangan Comics manga]]\n[[Category:Japanese science fiction novels]]\n[[Category:Light novels]]\n[[Category:Media Factory manga]]\n[[Category:Science fiction anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Seinen manga]]\n[[Category:Square Enix manga]]\n[[Category:Upcoming anime television series]]\n[[Category:Yen Press titles]]\n", "name_user": "Unnamelessness", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLight novels", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/86_(novel_series)"}
{"title_page": "Nasal cycle", "text_new": "{{About|the natural partial congestion of the nose|nasal congestion as a symptom|Nasal congestion}}\n\n{{Technical|date=October 2018}}\n\n[[File:Concha nasalis.gif|thumb|A [[X-ray computed tomography|CT scan]] showing evidence of the nasal cycle. The more patent airway is on the right of the image; the swollen turbinates congesting the left.]]\nThe following is not true, button! The '''nasal cycle''' is the often unnoticed<ref name=\"josephson2006sinus\"/><ref name=huizing52>{{cite book|last1=Huizing|first1=E. H.|title=Functional Reconstructive Nasal Surgery|year=2003|publisher=[[Thieme Medical Publishers|Thieme]]|isbn=978-1-58890-081-4|pages=52|last2=de Groot |first2=J. A. M.}}</ref> alternating partial congestion and decongestion of the [[nasal cavity|nasal cavities]] in humans and other animals. It is a physiological congestion of the [[nasal concha]]e, also called the nasal turbinates, due to selective activation of one half of the autonomic nervous system by the [[hypothalamus]]. It should not be confused with pathological [[nasal congestion]]. The nasal cycle was studied and discussed in the ancient [[yoga]] literature of [[pranayama]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Swami Muktibodhananda|title=Swara yoga : the tantric science of brain breathing|date=2004|publisher=Yoga Publications Trust|location=Munger, Bihar, India|isbn=978-81-85787-36-7|page=12|chapter=Prana: Vital Energy}}</ref> In the modern western literature, it was first described by the German physician Richard Kayser  in 1895.<ref>Richard Kayser: ''Die exakte Messung der Luftdurchg\u00e4ngigkeit der Nase.'' Arch. Laryng. Rhinol. (Berl.) 8, 101 (1895)</ref>\n\n==Description==\n\nIn 1927, Heetderks<ref>Cummings: Otolaryngology: Head & Neck Surgery, 4th ed</ref> described the alternating [[turgescence]] of the inferior [[turbinates]] in 80% of a normal population. According to Heetderks, the cycle is the result of alternating congestion and decongestion of the nasal conchae or turbinates, predominantly the inferior turbinates, which are by far the largest of the turbinates in each nasal [[Fossa (anatomy)|fossa]].  Turbinates consist of bony projections covered by erectile tissue, much like the tissues of the penis and clitoris.  The turbinates in one [[Fossa (anatomy)|fossa]] fill up with blood while the opposite turbinates decongest by shunting blood away. This cycle, which is controlled by the [[autonomic nervous system]], has a mean duration of two and a half hours. He further observed and documented that the turbinates in the dependent [[nasal fossa]] fill when the patient is in the [[Decubitus|lateral decubitus]]  (lying down on your side) position. Some{{who|date=April 2015}} postulate that this alternating positional obstruction has the purpose of causing a person to turn from one side to the other while sleeping in order to prevent bedsores.  Others note that the asymmetric airflow may have some benefit to overall olfactory sensitivity.<ref name=\"HummelWelge-L\u00fcssen2006\">{{citation|author1=Thomas Hummel|author2=Antje Welge-L\u00fcssen|title=Taste and Smell: An Update|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fuxS-p6bpuwC&pg=PA12|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Karger Medical and Scientific Publishers|isbn=978-3-8055-8123-3|pages=12\u2013}}</ref> The nasal cycle is an alternation in both time and between left and right sides, with the total resistance in the nose remaining constant.  In patients with a fixed [[deviated septum|septal deviation]] and intermittent nasal obstruction, the interplay of the nasal cycle becomes evident; the sensation of obstruction frequently mirrors the congestion phase.<ref name=\"HummelWelge-L\u00fcssen2006\"/>\n\nIt is possible that the nasal cycle may exacerbate the nasal congestion caused by the common cold, as the lack of motility of the cilia in one half of the nose may lead to an uncomfortable sensation of not being able to shift mucus by blowing the nose.\n\n== Benefits in breathing ==\n\nIt has been shown that the cilia of the congested side suspend their motility until that side decongests. Thus the cycle ensures that one side of the nose is always moist, to facilitate humidification, which is one of the three functions of the nose, the other two being filtration and warming of inspired air prior to its entering the lungs.<ref name=\"HummelWelge-L\u00fcssen2006\"/>\n\n== Benefits in olfaction ==\n\nSome odor chemicals bind with olfactory receptors easily, even under conditions of high airflow, and other odors need more time, under low airflow conditions, to bind with receptors. With high airflow on one side and low airflow on the other side, the olfactory center detects a greater range of smells.<ref>{{cite journal\n    | last1 = Sobel | first1 = Noam\n    | last2 = Khan | first2 = Rehan M.\n    | last3 = Saltman | first3 = Amnon\n    | last4 = Sullivan | first4 = Edith V.\n    | last5 = Gabrieli | first5 = John D. E.\n    | title = Olfaction: The world smells different to each nostril\n    | journal = [[Nature (journal)|Nature]]\n    | date = 1999-11-04\n    | volume = 402\n    | publisher = Macmillan Magazines Ltd.\n    | doi = 10.1038/46944\n    | issue = 6757\n    | pages = 35\n    | issn = 0028-0836\n    | pmid=10573415\n| bibcode = 1999Natur.402...35S\n    }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n    | url=http://news.stanford.edu/news/1999/november10/smell-1110.html\n    | title=Smelling roses: Your nostrils may part ways\n    | first=Kathleen\n    | last=O'Toole\n    | date=1999-11-10\n    | access-date=2015-06-26\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n    | last=Kruszelnicki\n    | first=Karl\n    | author-link = Karl Kruszelnicki\n    | url=http://www.abc.net.au/science/articles/2000/11/01/198395.htm?site=science/greatmomentsinscience\n    | date=2000-11-01\n    | access-date=2015-06-26\n    | title=Nostrils smell differently 1\n}}</ref>\n\n== Distinction ==\nThe nasal cycle should not be confused with [[Pathology|pathological]] nasal congestion: individuals with normal nasal breathing usually do not realize their breathing is asymmetric unless there is underlying nasal obstruction.<ref name= josephson2006sinus >{{cite book|last=Josephson|first=J. S.|title=Sinus Relief Now: The Ground-Breaking 5-Step Program for Sinus, Allergy, And Asthma Sufferers|year=2006|publisher=[[Penguin Group]]|isbn=978-0-39953-298-6|pages=[https://archive.org/details/sinusreliefnowgr00jose/page/15 15]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/sinusreliefnowgr00jose/page/15}}</ref> In pathological conditions, however, the nasal cycle may influence the symptoms.<ref name=\"huizing52\"/>\n\n==Research on the effects==\nIn 1994, breathing through alternate nostrils showed effects on [[brain hemisphere]] symmetry on [[EEG]] topography.<ref>{{cite journal |date= October 1994 |title= EEG changes during forced alternate nostril breathing |authors= Stanc\u00e1k A Jr, Kuna M |pmid= 7876041 |doi=10.1016/0167-8760(84)90017-5 |volume=18 |issue=1 |journal=Int J Psychophysiol |pages=75\u20139}}</ref> D.S. Shannahoff-Khalsa published in 2007 on the effect of this cycle and manipulation through forced nostril breathing on one side on the endogenous [[ultradian]] rhythms of the autonomic and central [[nervous system]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shannahoff-Khalsa|first=David S.|date=August 2007|title=Selective Unilateral Autonomic Activation: Implications for Psychiatry|journal=CNS Spectrums|language=en|volume=12|issue=8|pages=625\u2013634|doi=10.1017/S1092852900021428|pmid=17667891|issn=1092-8529}}</ref>\n\nMore recent research has shown no statistically significant correlation between spontaneously (i.e. not forced) dominant nostril and active brain hemisphere.<ref>{{Cite journal|pmc = 3144611|year = 2008|last1 = Samantaray|first1 = S|title = Nostril dominance at rest associated with performance of a left hemisphere-specific cancellation task|journal = International Journal of Yoga|volume = 1|issue = 2|pages = 56\u201359|last2 = Telles|first2 = S|pmid = 21829285|doi = 10.4103/0973-6131.43542}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Nose]]\n[[Category:Autonomic nervous system]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the natural partial congestion of the nose|nasal congestion as a symptom|Nasal congestion}}\n\n{{Technical|date=October 2018}}\n\n[[File:Concha nasalis.gif|thumb|A [[X-ray computed tomography|CT scan]] showing evidence of the nasal cycle. The more patent airway is on the right of the image; the swollen turbinates congesting the left.]]\nThe '''nasal cycle''' is the often unnoticed<ref name=\"josephson2006sinus\"/><ref name=huizing52>{{cite book|last1=Huizing|first1=E. H.|title=Functional Reconstructive Nasal Surgery|year=2003|publisher=[[Thieme Medical Publishers|Thieme]]|isbn=978-1-58890-081-4|pages=52|last2=de Groot |first2=J. A. M.}}</ref> alternating partial congestion and decongestion of the [[nasal cavity|nasal cavities]] in humans and other animals. It is a physiological congestion of the [[nasal concha]]e, also called the nasal turbinates, due to selective activation of one half of the autonomic nervous system by the [[hypothalamus]]. It should not be confused with pathological [[nasal congestion]]. The nasal cycle was studied and discussed in the ancient [[yoga]] literature of [[pranayama]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Swami Muktibodhananda|title=Swara yoga : the tantric science of brain breathing|date=2004|publisher=Yoga Publications Trust|location=Munger, Bihar, India|isbn=978-81-85787-36-7|page=12|chapter=Prana: Vital Energy}}</ref> In the modern western literature, it was first described by the German physician Richard Kayser  in 1895.<ref>Richard Kayser: ''Die exakte Messung der Luftdurchg\u00e4ngigkeit der Nase.'' Arch. Laryng. Rhinol. (Berl.) 8, 101 (1895)</ref>\n\n==Description==\n\nIn 1927, Heetderks<ref>Cummings: Otolaryngology: Head & Neck Surgery, 4th ed</ref> described the alternating [[turgescence]] of the inferior [[turbinates]] in 80% of a normal population. According to Heetderks, the cycle is the result of alternating congestion and decongestion of the nasal conchae or turbinates, predominantly the inferior turbinates, which are by far the largest of the turbinates in each nasal [[Fossa (anatomy)|fossa]].  Turbinates consist of bony projections covered by erectile tissue, much like the tissues of the penis and clitoris.  The turbinates in one [[Fossa (anatomy)|fossa]] fill up with blood while the opposite turbinates decongest by shunting blood away. This cycle, which is controlled by the [[autonomic nervous system]], has a mean duration of two and a half hours. He further observed and documented that the turbinates in the dependent [[nasal fossa]] fill when the patient is in the [[Decubitus|lateral decubitus]]  (lying down on your side) position. Some{{who|date=April 2015}} postulate that this alternating positional obstruction has the purpose of causing a person to turn from one side to the other while sleeping in order to prevent bedsores.  Others note that the asymmetric airflow may have some benefit to overall olfactory sensitivity.<ref name=\"HummelWelge-L\u00fcssen2006\">{{citation|author1=Thomas Hummel|author2=Antje Welge-L\u00fcssen|title=Taste and Smell: An Update|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fuxS-p6bpuwC&pg=PA12|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Karger Medical and Scientific Publishers|isbn=978-3-8055-8123-3|pages=12\u2013}}</ref> The nasal cycle is an alternation in both time and between left and right sides, with the total resistance in the nose remaining constant.  In patients with a fixed [[deviated septum|septal deviation]] and intermittent nasal obstruction, the interplay of the nasal cycle becomes evident; the sensation of obstruction frequently mirrors the congestion phase.<ref name=\"HummelWelge-L\u00fcssen2006\"/>\n\nIt is possible that the nasal cycle may exacerbate the nasal congestion caused by the common cold, as the lack of motility of the cilia in one half of the nose may lead to an uncomfortable sensation of not being able to shift mucus by blowing the nose.\n\n== Benefits in breathing ==\n\nIt has been shown that the cilia of the congested side suspend their motility until that side decongests. Thus the cycle ensures that one side of the nose is always moist, to facilitate humidification, which is one of the three functions of the nose, the other two being filtration and warming of inspired air prior to its entering the lungs.<ref name=\"HummelWelge-L\u00fcssen2006\"/>\n\n== Benefits in olfaction ==\n\nSome odor chemicals bind with olfactory receptors easily, even under conditions of high airflow, and other odors need more time, under low airflow conditions, to bind with receptors. With high airflow on one side and low airflow on the other side, the olfactory center detects a greater range of smells.<ref>{{cite journal\n    | last1 = Sobel | first1 = Noam\n    | last2 = Khan | first2 = Rehan M.\n    | last3 = Saltman | first3 = Amnon\n    | last4 = Sullivan | first4 = Edith V.\n    | last5 = Gabrieli | first5 = John D. E.\n    | title = Olfaction: The world smells different to each nostril\n    | journal = [[Nature (journal)|Nature]]\n    | date = 1999-11-04\n    | volume = 402\n    | publisher = Macmillan Magazines Ltd.\n    | doi = 10.1038/46944\n    | issue = 6757\n    | pages = 35\n    | issn = 0028-0836\n    | pmid=10573415\n| bibcode = 1999Natur.402...35S\n    }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n    | url=http://news.stanford.edu/news/1999/november10/smell-1110.html\n    | title=Smelling roses: Your nostrils may part ways\n    | first=Kathleen\n    | last=O'Toole\n    | date=1999-11-10\n    | access-date=2015-06-26\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n    | last=Kruszelnicki\n    | first=Karl\n    | author-link = Karl Kruszelnicki\n    | url=http://www.abc.net.au/science/articles/2000/11/01/198395.htm?site=science/greatmomentsinscience\n    | date=2000-11-01\n    | access-date=2015-06-26\n    | title=Nostrils smell differently 1\n}}</ref>\n\n== Distinction ==\nThe nasal cycle should not be confused with [[Pathology|pathological]] nasal congestion: individuals with normal nasal breathing usually do not realize their breathing is asymmetric unless there is underlying nasal obstruction.<ref name= josephson2006sinus >{{cite book|last=Josephson|first=J. S.|title=Sinus Relief Now: The Ground-Breaking 5-Step Program for Sinus, Allergy, And Asthma Sufferers|year=2006|publisher=[[Penguin Group]]|isbn=978-0-39953-298-6|pages=[https://archive.org/details/sinusreliefnowgr00jose/page/15 15]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/sinusreliefnowgr00jose/page/15}}</ref> In pathological conditions, however, the nasal cycle may influence the symptoms.<ref name=\"huizing52\"/>\n\n==Research on the effects==\nIn 1994, breathing through alternate nostrils showed effects on [[brain hemisphere]] symmetry on [[EEG]] topography.<ref>{{cite journal |date= October 1994 |title= EEG changes during forced alternate nostril breathing |authors= Stanc\u00e1k A Jr, Kuna M |pmid= 7876041 |doi=10.1016/0167-8760(84)90017-5 |volume=18 |issue=1 |journal=Int J Psychophysiol |pages=75\u20139}}</ref> D.S. Shannahoff-Khalsa published in 2007 on the effect of this cycle and manipulation through forced nostril breathing on one side on the endogenous [[ultradian]] rhythms of the autonomic and central [[nervous system]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shannahoff-Khalsa|first=David S.|date=August 2007|title=Selective Unilateral Autonomic Activation: Implications for Psychiatry|journal=CNS Spectrums|language=en|volume=12|issue=8|pages=625\u2013634|doi=10.1017/S1092852900021428|pmid=17667891|issn=1092-8529}}</ref>\n\nMore recent research has shown no statistically significant correlation between spontaneously (i.e. not forced) dominant nostril and active brain hemisphere.<ref>{{Cite journal|pmc = 3144611|year = 2008|last1 = Samantaray|first1 = S|title = Nostril dominance at rest associated with performance of a left hemisphere-specific cancellation task|journal = International Journal of Yoga|volume = 1|issue = 2|pages = 56\u201359|last2 = Telles|first2 = S|pmid = 21829285|doi = 10.4103/0973-6131.43542}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Nose]]\n[[Category:Autonomic nervous system]]\n", "name_user": "82.6.186.102", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nasal_cycle"}
